<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many, but not all, scandals at banks are cause=
d by the facts that (1) the bank wants to make money, (2) it gives its empl=
oyees incentives to make money, (3) they are under a lot of pressure to per=
form and (4) making money is hard. (In this, the bank employees are much li=
ke the insider trading AI.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the most normal kind of banking scandal is =
that the employees do things to make money that are either risky (and thus =
bad for the bank) or fraud-y (and thus bad for the bank=E2=80=99s customers=
 from whom they make the money). Another, somewhat less common=C2=A0kind of=
 scandal is that the employees=C2=A0<em>pretend=C2=A0</em>to make money. Th=
ey just, like, write in their daily report, =E2=80=9CI made a lot of money =
today,=E2=80=9D and their bosses are deceived, and the bank thinks it has m=
oney that it doesn=E2=80=99t. There are various <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33523803.281430/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub=
